sentences: Irving Sidney "Duke" Jordan (April 1, 1922 – August 8, 2006) was an American jazz pianist.
An imaginative and gifted pianist, Jordan was a regular member of Charlie Parker's quintet during 1947–48, which also featured Miles Davis.
He participated in Parker's Dial sessions in late 1947 that produced "Dewey Square", "Bongo Bop", "Bird of Paradise", and the ballad "Embraceable You".
Beginning in 1978, he lived in Copenhagen, Denmark, having  recorded an extensive sequence of albums for the SteepleChase label;  his first record date for the company was in 1973.
